{{Expand Hebrew|מרדכי ברויאר (היסטוריון)|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox person | name = Mordechai Breuer | image = Prof. Mordechai Breuer.jpg | alt = | caption = Prof. Mordechai Breuer | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1918|4|8|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Frankfurt]], [[Hesse-Nassau]], [[German Empire|Germany]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2007|5|28|1918|4|8|df=y}} | death_place = [[Israel]] | nationality = [[Israel]]i | other_names = | occupation = | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | parents = [[Isaac Breuer]] and Jenny Eisenmann }}
'''Mordechai Breuer''' (1918–2007) was a German-Jewish Historian and writer.
==Background and Family== Breuer was born in [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt am Main]] (Germany) to [[Isaac Breuer]] and his wife Jenny Breuer (née Eisenmann) in 1918. He had four siblings: [[Jacob Breuer|Yaakov]]; [[Ursula Merkin|Ulla]], Tzipora, and Simeon. The family originated in [[Frankfurt]] but left for [[Israel]] in 1936.
==Work== Breuer wrote extensively on History, particularly German Jewish History. His works include ''Modernity Within Tradition: The Social History of Orthodox Jewry in Imperial Germany,'' (Columbia University Press: 1992) and ''The Torah-im-Derekh-Eretz of S.R. Hirsch'' (1970).
== References == * German-Jewish history in modern times, Volume 1, By Michael A. Meyer, Mordechai Breuer, Michael Graetz * Marc B. Shapiro, [https://seforim.blogspot.com/2007/06/marc-b-shapiro-obituary-for-prof.html Obituary for Professor Mordechai Breuer zt”l], the Seforim Blog * פיוטים בביצועו, מתוך אתר "פיוט" * http://www.jewishpress.com/printArticle.cfm?contentid=21793 {{Reflist}}
