{{other people||Richard Cohen (disambiguation)}} {{BLP sources|date=February 2011}} '''Richard I. (Yerachmiel)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewish.huji.ac.il/faculty/history_faculty/cohen.html |title=Richard (Yerachmiel) Cohen |publisher=The Hebrew University of Jerusalem |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915090026/http://jewish.huji.ac.il/faculty/history_faculty/cohen.html|archive-date=15 September 2007 |accessdate=2016-10-04}}</ref> Cohen''' (born September 2, 1946) is a professor of history, presently holding the Paulette and Claude Kelman Chair in [[History of the Jews in France|French Jewry]] Studies in the Department of [[Jewish]] [[History]] at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]. He specializes in the history of Jews in Western and Central Europe in the modern period, in particular the Jews of France, art history, Jewish historiography, and [[The Holocaust]].<ref name="bio">{{cite web |url=http://www.huji.ac.il/dataj/controller/ihoker/MOP-STAFF_LINK?sno=9755180 |title=Richard I. Cohen |publisher=The Hebrew University of Jerusalem|accessdate=2016-10-04}}</ref>
==Biography== Cohen completed his undergraduate degree at [[McGill University]] in 1967. He earned his master's degree in 1972 and PhD in 1981, both at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.<ref name="bio"/>
He was on the international editorial board of the ''[[Encyclopaedia of the Holocaust]]'', published in 1990 in tandem [[Hebrew language|Hebrew-]] and [[English-language]] editions by [[Yad Vashem]].
Cohen's 1998 book ''Jewish Icons: Art and Society in Modern Europe'' explores art by and about Jews, in the context of European Jewish social history, as well as art history, and encompasses both high art and popular visual culture;<ref>Soussloff, Catherine M. Review of ''Jewish Icons: Art and Society in Modern Europe'', by Richard I. Cohen. ''Central European History'' 33.1 (2000): p. 122-25; here: p. 122. Available via JSTOR: [https://www.jstor.org/stable/4546944] (registration required).</ref> he produced this work in the course of a 15-year collaboration with fellow Hebrew University historian Ezra Mendelsohn (1940-2015)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huji.ac.il/dataj/controller/ihoker/MOP-STAFF_LINK?sno=9881701 |title=Ezra Mendelsohn |publisher=The Hebrew University of Jerusalem |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref> in efforts to encourage research on the arts and modern Jewish society.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-msUBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA381 |page=381 (footnote 2) |title=The Art of Being Jewish in Modern Times |last1=Kirshenblatt-Gimblett |first1=Barbara |last2=Karp |first2=Jonathan |year=2007 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |isbn=978-0-8122-4002-3}} In the introduction, the editors credit Cohen and Mendelsohn (p. 1) with conceiving the seminar "Modern Jewry and the Arts" (held in academic year 2000-2001 at the Center for Advanced Judaic Studies, University of Pennsylvania) which was the basis of the edited volume, and state, in the cited footnote: "This seminar was the most recent in a series of efforts by Richard I. Cohen and Ezra Mendelsohn over the last fifteen years to encourage work on this topic."</ref>
==Selected bibliography== *{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d8JtAAAAMAAJ&q=inauthor:%22Richard+I.+Cohen%22&dq=inauthor:%22Richard+I.+Cohen%22&hl=en&ei=kWFUTY7hHoqKhQfsx7yyCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEEQ6AEwBQ |title=The Return to the Land of Israel |year=1968 |publisher=World Zionist Organization, Dor Hemschech |isbn=965-227-035-0}} (co-author: Judith Carp) *{{cite book |title=Burden of Conscience: French-Jewish leadership during the Holocaust |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MkPKmNqDjLcC&q=burden+of+conscience&dq=burden+of+conscience&hl=en&ei=ZmFUTfS7N56qhAfUp43gCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCYQ6AEwAA |year=1987 |publisher=Indiana University Press |isbn=0-253-31263-9}} *{{cite book |title=Jewish Icons: Art and society in Modern Europe'' |publisher=University of California Press |year=1998 |isbn=0-520-20545-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pZAp3SWO-TYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=richard+i.+cohen&hl=en&ei=EWFUTY2mCM25hAfquOGICQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false}} *{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R_TpAAAAMAAJ&q=richard+cohen+hebrew+university&dq=richard+cohen+hebrew+university&hl=en&ei=kGxUTau7KoG2hAfT0ZjmCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8&ved=0CGEQ6AEwBw |title=The Emergence of Jewish Artists in Nineteenth-Century Europe |year=2001 |publisher=Merrill |isbn=1-85894-153-9}} (co-author: Susan Tumarkin Goodman) *{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N6RtAAAAMAAJ&q=diary+of+a+witness&dq=diary+of+a+witness&hl=en&ei=wGRUTdKJK5S0hAeVorG7Bg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAg |title=Diary of a Witness: 1940-1943 |publisher=Ivan R. Dee |year=2007 |isbn=1-56663-740-6}} (editor) *{{cite book |title=The Jewish Contribution to Civilization: Reassessing an idea |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t5TtAAAAMAAJ&q=inauthor:%22Richard+I.+Cohen%22&dq=inauthor:%22Richard+I.+Cohen%22&hl=en&ei=kWFUTY7hHoqKhQfsx7yyCQ&sa=X&oi=